node.text:
Frames from a camera that spent three moonless nights under the stars in the village of Magyaregres, Hungary create this composite night skyscape. They were recorded during August 11-13 while planet Earth was sweeping through the dusty trail of comet Swift-Tuttle. The radiant effect is due only to perspective, as the parallel tracks appear to converge in the distance against the starry sky.

📸: NASA

Though these images can be captured at the ISS, it's hard to put into perspective the relentless urban sprawl of humanity. Here, Las Vegas explodes in size between 1989 and 2019, quadrupling its population from 710,000 people to 3 million. See more Earth transformations at the link in the bio. 

📸: European Space Agency

Shhhh. Do you hear that? Neither do I.

NASA’s X-59 Quiet SuperSonic Technology X-plane is designed to fly faster than the speed of sound without producing sonic booms – those loud, startling noises which can be disruptive to humans and animals. This experimental plane will fly at a cruise speed roughly double that of a commercial jet while keeping aircraft noise down to a quiet “sonic thump” – or even no sound at all – as heard on the ground when the plane flies overhead at supersonic speeds. 

To be sure the X-59’s design will perform within expected noise limits, NASA is working closely with its contractor, Lockheed Martin, to create a database of computational fluid dynamics simulations to verify the aircraft’s supersonic performance.

📸: NASA/James C. Jensen
